SIMPLE: inclemency
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Inclemency
<hw>In*clem"en*cy</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Inclemencies</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>inclementia</ets>: cf. F. <ets>incl⟦eacute⟧mence</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The state or quality of being inclement; lack of
clemency; lack of mildness of temper; unmercifulness;
severity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>inclemency</qex> of the late pope.</q> <rj><qau>Bp.
Hall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Physical severity or harshness (commonly in respect
to the elements or weather); roughness; storminess; rigor; severe cold,
wind, rain, or snow.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The <qex>inclemencies</qex> of morning air.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The rude <qex>inclemency</qex> of wintry skies.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowper.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Harshness; severity; cruelty; rigor; roughness;
storminess; boisterousness.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Inclement</ent>⟦br⟧
